  "prompt": "How was the International Space Station built?",
  "response": "The International Space Station (ISS) is a collaborative project involving space agencies from multiple countries, including NASA (United States), Roscosmos (Russia), JAXA (Japan), ESA (European Space Agency), and CSA (Canada). Its construction was a complex process that took place over several years and involved multiple stages:\n\n1. **Initial Planning (1984-1993)**:\n   - Conceptual discussions and negotiations began in the 1980s.\n   - The project received go-ahead in 1984 from U.S. President Ronald Reagan.\n   - Partnerships were formed with other major space agencies.\n\n2. **Early Modules (1998-2000)**:\n   - The first module of the ISS, Zarya (\"Sunrise\"), a Russian-built module funded by the United States, was launched on November 20, 1998.\n   - Unity, an American-built connecting module, was launched shortly after, in December 1998.\n   \n3. **Assembly in Orbit**:\n   - The construction of the ISS involved assembling multiple modules, trusses, and other components in space.\n   - This was done using various space shuttle missions and Russian rockets.\n   - Key modules include Destiny (a laboratory module from NASA), Zvezda (a Russian service module), Japanese Experiment Module, Columbus (ESA laboratory), and others.\n\n4. **Expansion and Upgrades**:\n   - As more modules were added, the station expanded in size and functionality.\n   - Key truss segments provided structural support and housed solar panels.\n   - Robotic systems like Canadarm2 (a robotic arm) played crucial roles in assembling and maintaining the station.\n\n5. **Continuous Crews**:\n   - Since the arrival of the Expedition 1 crew in October 2000, the ISS has been continually inhabited.\n   - International crews have conducted scientific research and maintained the station.\n\n6. **International Collaboration**:\n   - The ISS is a symbol of global cooperation in space exploration.\n   - Multiple nations contribute to its operations, research efforts, and crew rotations.\n\nThe ISS continues to function as a hub for scientific research, international cooperation, and technology development, aiding our understanding of living and working in space.",
